Anonymous Sun 22 Mar 2020 00:55:10 No.29109351 Report
Quoted By: >>29110269
>>29108514
>images
Absolutely
Having an actual picture of the scene can not only help immensely to give readers a more unified and accurate idea of what characters locations look like, even more so when concerning building layouts, but also allow you to put in things that you can use later without being called a hack or inconsistent because it either wasn't important enough to have any of the characters mention or would've made it glaringly obvious that it was going to be relevant later
>songs
If you mean just having a song that the reader is supposed to listen during a given scene then probably not, that should be left mostly to actual animated stories or scenes. However you could use a song playing over a radio in the car, for example, to give pacing to a conversation if you need a way to stress that it's moving very quickly or slowly; you'd have to do some weird structuring of the physical placement of the words on the page but you could do something like having the conversation on the left half with the song on the right half; went ahead and made this rough visual of what I mean by that, though that still depends on the reader either already knowing the song and having decent enough memory to get a grasp on how it sets the pacing or them being willing to listen to the song for the scene which could also run into trouble if they are too fast a reader, even worse if they can't read fast enough because the fast one can just wait, and there's still the issue of how to present the song to the reader. Should it be linked right there in the regular text? Link them in a separate document with their locations written out beside each of them? Just leave it up to the reader to look up the song of their own volition? I also can't see any way to make use of any songs with little or no vocals
Though do take all of my advice with an increased degree of skepticism as I am no writefag nor do I have any experience in writing beyond whatever I did in highschool English classes

Top and bottom in black text are just the normal story
Left is a conversation between two people
Right is supposed to be lyrics of a song that's there to show the speed of the conversation, the placement of words on the left and right are supposed to match chronologically, hence why there's the ellipses, to show that the two people are still speaking in the time in between lines
Hopefully this update helps
~6 seconds in person A finishes their first sentence / The song has gone through its first two lines, a short period of music without lyrics, and its third line
~14 seconds in the person B finishes their first sentence / The song has gone through a longer period of music without lyrics and its fourth line
~26 seconds in person A finishes their second sentence / The song has gone through its fifth line, another short period of music without lyrics, its sixth line, a slightly longer period of music without lyrics, and its seventh line
~35 seconds in person B finishes their second sentence / The song has gone through its twelfth line and entered a short period of music without lyrics
~38 seconds in person A finishes their third sentence / The song has gotten halfway through its thirteenth line
~49 seconds in person B finishes their third sentence / The song completed its thirteenth line, its fourteenth line, a short period of music without lyrics, its fifteenth line, and a slightly longer period of music without lyrics (it continues even after the story returns to normal text, but as there is no conversation happening the song is no longer mentioned, having served its purpose
That's probably a very autistic way of explaining it but oh well

What I've done twice is to write the first draft without concern for beats.
I figure a series of events, and insert extras where they're called for.
I usually have a starting point and end. Whether that first start is actually the middle of the story isn't important. Establish the characters and setting.
Somewhere between the middle and end I develop a strong sense of the backstory and themes, so I rewrite from that.

I prefer doing drafts because my initial ideas rarely match what I learn by writing the story. Everyone has the amount of structure that's correct for them and the story.

We're already drowning in a near endless stream of virtually identical media, but somehow I still can't get a lot of the shit I actually want because as soon as it's done once people are shy to do it again. Unless, of course, it's one of those things that's been done so often it's essentially a genre. So you have dozens upon dozens of identical cop shows, horror movies, whatever. because it's somehow not a ripoff anymore when you fail to show even the least amount of originality.
